# Day 79 – Compliance Checklists and Self-Assessment | 100 Days of GRC
*By Ibrahim Abdullahi | 100-Day GRC Challenge: Securing OpenMRS on AWS*

---

## The Internal Radar — Self-Assessment Before Auditors Arrive

Day 78 built out the POA&M management discipline — the timeline revision process, ownership enforcement, the 90-day aging review, and the formal risk acceptance process. The POA&M tracks gaps that are already identified. Day 79 is about the practice that surfaces gaps before they appear in a formal assessment or, worse, in a breach investigation: structured self-assessment using compliance checklists.

I want to be direct about where I am starting from with this topic. The term "compliance checklist" can mean very different things depending on how it is used. At its worst, a compliance checklist is exactly what the phrase "check-the-box compliance" describes — a table with a column of requirements and a column of yes/no answers, completed under time pressure before an audit, with the goal of generating a passing score rather than an accurate picture of the organization's security posture. At its best, a compliance checklist is a structured self-interrogation that forces the organization to look at its own controls honestly, surface gaps, and feed the findings into the POA&M and continuous monitoring program.

The difference is not the format. It is the intent and the follow-through. Today I want to examine what makes self-assessment genuinely useful rather than theater.

---

## What I Worked On Today

Compliance self-assessment is a practice supported by multiple frameworks — NIST SP 800-53A provides assessment procedures for each control in the 800-53 control catalog, the HHS HIPAA Security Rule has an official self-assessment guidance document, CIS Controls provide implementation verification checklists, and the AWS Well-Architected Framework security pillar provides cloud-specific self-assessment questions. Today I work through what a substantive self-assessment looks like for the OpenMRS deployment — not a single checklist pass but a multi-framework self-assessment structure that covers the most important gaps an internal reviewer should surface before a formal re-authorization assessment.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The concept that clarified self-assessment today is understanding the difference between a compliance assertion and a compliance demonstration.

A compliance assertion is a statement: "Yes, we encrypt data at rest." A compliance demonstration is the evidence and context that makes the assertion verifiable: "RDS instance encryption is enabled using customer-managed KMS key [ARN]. S3 backup bucket has server-side encryption enabled with AES-256. EC2 EBS volumes were created with encryption enabled as the account default. Config rule `rds-storage-encrypted` has been COMPLIANT continuously since [date]. The most recent Audit Manager evidence collection [date] shows these controls in compliant state."

Most compliance checklists produce assertions. Effective self-assessment produces demonstrations. The difference matters because assertions can be wrong — not through dishonesty, but through incomplete knowledge. The ISSO who asserts "we log access to patient records" may be genuinely believing that assertion, based on knowing that CloudTrail is enabled and OpenMRS has an audit log module. The ISSO who demonstrates compliance needs to actually verify that the OpenMRS audit log is capturing read events for patient records, that those events include the required fields (who, what, when, from where), that the logs are flowing to CloudWatch, and that the CloudWatch log retention is configured to meet the HIPAA requirement. The demonstration process frequently discovers that the assertion was only partially accurate.

This is why self-assessment is valuable even for a well-monitored system: the monitoring program watches for deviations from the known configuration. Self-assessment questions whether the known configuration is actually what was implemented and verified. It catches the gap between what we think we have and what we actually have.

