## NIST SP 800-53A Self-Assessment — Selected High-Value Controls

NIST SP 800-53A provides examine, interview, and test procedures for every control in the 800-53 catalog. Self-assessment using 800-53A procedures is the closest approximation to what an external assessor will do at re-authorization — not as rigorous, because the ISSO lacks the independence of an external assessor, but using the same methodology.

---

**AU-2 / AU-12 — Audit Logging: Self-Assessment Test**

The formal assessment (Day 59) verified that the four required event types were being captured with all required fields. Nine months later: is this still true?

Self-assessment test: Log in to OpenMRS as a test user. Perform each of the four required event types: (1) successful authentication, (2) failed authentication attempt, (3) record modification, (4) privilege escalation attempt (attempt to access a function outside the assigned role).

Then: Open the OpenMRS audit log. Verify that all four events appear in the log within 60 seconds of occurrence. Verify that each event includes: user ID, event type, timestamp, and patient record identifier where applicable.

*Result:* Events 1, 2, and 3 confirmed in audit log with all required fields. Event 4 (privilege escalation attempt) generated an access denial message in the application but did not generate an audit log entry. The denied access was not logged.

*Self-assessment finding:* AU-12 gap — denied access attempts are not being logged. This is a control effectiveness degradation since the formal assessment. The formal assessment verified that access control enforcement worked (denied access correctly); the self-assessment reveals that the logging of denied access events is not functioning as documented.

*Severity:* Moderate — the gap reduces the ISSO's ability to detect patterns of unauthorized access attempts that are consistently denied. A determined attacker probing for role escalation vulnerabilities would not appear in the audit log.

*Action:* Investigate whether a recent OpenMRS update changed the audit module configuration. Determine whether this requires an OpenMRS module configuration fix or an application update. Create POA&M item. Notify AO per Condition 3 (Moderate finding from continuous monitoring).

This finding illustrates exactly why self-assessment using test procedures — not just configuration review — is necessary even for a monitored system. The Config rules and Security Hub monitoring would not have detected this gap because it is an application-layer logging failure, not an infrastructure configuration issue.

---

**CP-3 — Contingency Plan Training: Self-Assessment Interview**

Self-assessment question: Ask two clinical staff members — without advance notice and without leading questions — to describe what they would do if OpenMRS became unavailable during a patient encounter.

*Result of informal conversations:*

Staff member 1 (clinical nurse): "I would go get the downtime forms from the supply cabinet. Dr. [name] showed us where they are when we first started." Correct general approach, but this staff member referred to a training session conducted during onboarding — not the formal CP-3 training from the POA&M item 002 completion.

Staff member 2 (administrative coordinator): "I'm not sure — I think we have paper forms? I've never had to use them." This staff member has not internalized the downtime procedure even after the training module was delivered.

*Self-assessment finding:* CP-3 training completion is documented, but retention is not verified. Documenting that staff completed a training module and verifying that staff can actually recall and execute the procedure are different standards. The CP-2 downtime procedure (POA&M item 001, near-deadline at Day 73) is the document; CP-3 training is the human readiness to use it. The informal conversation reveals that readiness is incomplete.

*Action:* Add a brief retention check to the next quarterly training review — not a formal test, but a structured conversation with a sample of staff to verify retention of the key downtime procedure elements. Document the check and its results.

