## The Self-Assessment Scorecard

After working through the multi-framework self-assessment, the findings are organized into a brief scorecard that goes to the Health IT Manager:

| Area | Framework | Finding | Severity | Action |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Risk analysis currency | HIPAA §164.308(a)(1) | No comprehensive re-analysis since authorization | Low | Add to annual CM summary |
| Login history training | HIPAA §164.308(a)(5) | Users not trained to review own login history | Low | Next AT-2 cycle |
| Denied access logging | NIST AU-12 | Denied access events not appearing in audit log | Moderate | POA&M; AO notification |
| CP-3 training retention | NIST CP-3 | Staff retention incomplete after training completion | Low | Quarterly retention check |
| Long-term IAM access key | AWS Well-Architected | CloudWatch agent using long-term key | Low | Quarterly change cycle |
| IR-3 tabletop exercise | NIST IR-3 | Exercise not yet conducted | Low (existing POA&M item 004) | Priority scheduling |

Six findings in one structured self-assessment session. One is Moderate and requires AO notification. The others are Low. All are now tracked and assigned.

This is the genuine value of periodic self-assessment: the AU-12 denied-access logging gap would likely not have surfaced through the standard monitoring program before re-authorization. Config rules don't test application-layer logging. Security Hub doesn't evaluate OpenMRS audit log completeness. The ISSO's manual test — log in, do something denied, check the log — is what found it.

