## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The CP-3 training retention finding — staff completing training modules without retaining actionable knowledge — is the exact pattern that contributed to the **2016 Hollywood Presbyterian Medical Center ransomware incident**, where the hospital paid a $17,000 Bitcoin ransom after ransomware encrypted systems and staff were unable to execute manual downtime procedures effectively.

Post-incident accounts indicated that staff had not been adequately drilled on paper-based downtime procedures and that the ransomware incident — which lasted approximately ten days — created significant clinical operational chaos precisely because the muscle memory for operating without the EHR had not been developed through regular practice.

The self-assessment question — asking two staff members without advance notice to describe what they would do if OpenMRS was unavailable — is the lightweight equivalent of the drilled readiness that Hollywood Presbyterian lacked. The goal is not a formal exam. It is a reality check: do the people who would need to execute the downtime procedure actually know what to do, or do they know that a document exists that they have never read?

The distinction between documented readiness and genuine readiness is what CP-3 training is designed to address. The self-assessment finding that one out of two clinical staff could not describe the downtime procedure is a low-cost early warning that the training has not achieved its intended outcome.

