## What I Am Still Thinking About

The AU-12 denied-access logging finding is the most significant outcome of today's self-assessment — it is a Moderate finding requiring AO notification, discovered through a test procedure rather than automated monitoring. I want to think about why this gap appeared.

The formal assessment (Day 59) verified that denied access was being detected and denied correctly — the assessor tested three cross-role access attempts and all three were rejected. But the assessor tested whether the control enforcement was working, not whether the logging of denied enforcement was working. The two are different aspects of the same control.

The ISSO who designed the continuous monitoring program (Day 52) included monitoring for access control effectiveness but oriented the monitoring toward active intrusion detection (GuardDuty unusual patterns, failed authentication alerts) rather than toward verification that the audit log was capturing all required event types continuously.

The gap this reveals: the M-2 ongoing assessment program should include a periodic audit log completeness test — actually generating each of the required event types in the test environment and verifying they appear in the log with all required fields. This is different from verifying that the logging configuration is enabled (which Config rules check) — it is verifying that the logging configuration produces complete and accurate logs (which requires a test).

I want to add a semi-annual audit log completeness test to the M-2 assessment schedule: generate each required event type in the test environment, verify each appears in the CloudWatch log group with the required fields, and document the test results in the monitoring log. This is the kind of test that catches AU-12 degradation before re-authorization rather than during it.

